Okay, I understand the task. We need to move the red ball from (50, 100) to (250, 50) through collaboration. First, I need to figure out my current location to determine how to proceed.

```
[
  { "cmd": "sense" }
]
```

Now I am at (50, 100), facing North (90 degrees). I am at the location of the red ball. I will pick it up. Then, I will broadcast to other robots.

```
[
  { "cmd": "pick" }
]
```

Okay, I picked up the red ball. Now, I need to broadcast to other robots to coordinate the handover. I see that trial2\_robot3 is at (250, 150) and is willing to receive the ball. I will propose a handover point midway between our x-coordinates, and at the destination's y-coordinate. This will make it easier for both of us. The handover point will be ((50+250)/2, 50) = (150, 50). I'll ask trial2\_robot3 to move to (150, 50) to receive the ball. I will move to (150, 50) as well.

```
[
  { "cmd": "broadcast", "data": "This is trial2_robot1: I have the red ball. trial2_robot3, please move to the handover point (150, 50). I will also move there." }
]
```

I am at (50.2, 100.1) facing 84.8 degrees. I need to pick up the red ball, then go to trial2\_robot3 at (250.1, 50.1).

```
[
  { "cmd": "pick" }
]
```

I am at (50.3, 100.1) facing 79.6 degrees. I need to pick up the red ball, then go to trial2\_robot3 at (250.1, 50.1).
```
[
  { "cmd": "pick" }
]
```

It seems like I am trapped in a loop. I keep returning to (44.8, 70.4). I need to rethink my strategy. I will ask trial2_robot3 to come to me instead. I will move to x=50, y=50, which is closer to the center of my boundary.
```
[
  { "cmd": "broadcast", "data": "This is trial2_robot1: I am stuck in a loop. trial2_robot3, can you come to me at (50, 50) to pick up the ball?" }
]
```
